 Virtual Hosting on Apache (Fedora)
This section covers configuring multiple websites on one Apache server using Virtual Hosts.

 1. Create Directories for Each Website you want to create:
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/html/example1(mywebsite)
sudo mkdir -p /var/www/html/example2
sudo chown -R $USER:$USER /var/www/html/example*
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/www/html/example*

2. HTTP Virtual Host for Redirection (Port 80)
Create configuration file:
sudo nano /etc/httpd/conf.d/mywebsite.conf
It should look like this:
<VirtualHost *:80>
    ServerName mywebsite.com
    ServerAlias www.mywebsite.com

    # Redirect all HTTP traffic to HTTPS
    Redirect "/" "https://mywebsite.com/"

    ErrorLog /var/log/httpd/mywebsite-error.log
    CustomLog /var/log/httpd/mywebsite-access.log combined
</VirtualHost>

3. Directory Permissions for Virtual Hosts
sudo chcon -R -t httpd_sys_content_t /var/www/html/example1
sudo chcon -R -t httpd_sys_content_t /var/www/html/example2

4. Test Virtual Hosts
sudo apachectl configtest
sudo systemctl restart httpd
Visit:
http://example1.com
http://example2.com

5. Add Your Homepage to Virtual Hosts
sudo nano /var/www/html/example1/index.html
Write:
html
<h1>Welcome to Imani's Website</h1>
Repeat for other sites as needed.

6.Testing the Website
In your web browser:
http://mywebsite.com

Should redirect automatically to:
https://mywebsite.com

Your homepage should display:
“Welcome to Imani's Website” or whatever you added for your homepage
